"RAAS", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9899575114250183, "span": {"begin": 437, "end": 441}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:59272"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ACE2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9924008846282959, "span": {"begin": 497, "end": 501}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mRNA", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.8428720235824585, "span": {"begin": 523, "end": 527}}, {"id": ["mesh:D045169"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "SARS-CoV", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.7537539601325989, "span": {"begin": 578, "end": 586}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SARS-CoV-2", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.86544269323349, "span": {"begin": 578, "end": 588}}], "text": "The current KER relates to evidence for downregulation of the ACE2 following the binding of the viral spike S protein of SARS-COV (1 or 2).  According to the evidence (mostly from the study of SARS-CoV-1 in the years preceding the SARS-CoV-2 emergence and the COVID-19 pandemic) the infection of cells by SARS-CoV leads to downregulation of ACE2, either:  - in the form of&nbsp;shedding of the ACE2 (which has other repercussions from a RAAS point of view)  - internalization / endocytosis of the ACE2  - downregulation of mRNA / protein expression.  The literature focusing on SARS-CoV-2 is quite scarce, especially in relation to animal work (only 5 studies have been identified) up to November 2021.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:32:18 +0000 2026"}